"analysis": "We computed global-P95 anomalies and drilled down into top KPIs for frontends and some checkoutservice pods. Results show frontends (frontend-0/1/2, frontend2-0) have the highest anomaly counts and concentrated error_log entries starting ~15:30. However, KPI-level 'fault runs' (consecutive breaches) for the selected top KPIs are short (single-minute spikes) and do not meet the conservative 'likely_fault' criteria (>=2 minutes and severity_ratio>0.5). Thus metrics alone did not produce a single clear sustained fault timestamp. Error logs are heavily concentrated on frontend pods and likely contain textual clues about underlying causes (e.g., upstream fetch failures). To identify the two distinct failures and their exact occurrence times we should analyze error_log message patterns and their time distribution to locate distinct failure peaks and extract earliest error timestamps and message types. This will guide targeted trace and metric re-inspection for the precise root cause component and reason.",
"completed": "False",
"instruction": "From error_df (already in kernel) perform an incident-window analysis for frontend pods only (cmdb_id in ['frontend-0','frontend-1','frontend-2']):\n1) Filter error_df to timestamps between '2022-03-20 15:30:00' and '2022-03-20 16:00:00' Asia/Shanghai and cmdb_id in the frontend list.\n2) For each unique message pattern, where pattern = first 120 characters of the 'message' field, compute: total_count (number of rows), earliest_error_timestamp, latest_error_timestamp. Return the top 10 patterns ranked by total_count, showing: pattern_text (first 120 chars), total_count, earliest_error_timestamp, latest_error_timestamp. Also return up to 5 full sample messages (full 'message' strings) for each of these top patterns.\n3) Additionally, produce a per-minute error count series for these frontend pods within the incident window: for each minute timestamp (floored to minute as in data) report timestamp, total_error_count across the three frontends, and per-pod counts for frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2. Return the full per-minute series (up to 30 rows).\nKeep outputs compact (patterns limited to 10 rows; sample messages up to 5 per pattern; per-minute series up to 30 rows). Store results in kernel variables error_patterns_df and frontend_error_timeseries. Return the two tables as plain text."  
}

